#yum update -y
	yum 	→ The package manager used in RHEL/CentOS/Amazon Linux systems (older versions; newer ones use dnf).
	update 	→ Tells yum to update all installed packages to the latest available versions from the configured repositories.
	-y 		→ Automatically answers "yes" to all prompts, so the update runs without asking for confirmation.

#yum install -y docker

#systemctl enable docker && systemctl start docker
	systemctl enable docker
		Registers Docker to start automatically at boot.
		Creates symlinks in /etc/systemd/system/... so the service is enabled on system startup.
		Does not start Docker immediately, just ensures it will run after every reboot.
	systemctl start docker
		Starts the Docker daemon right now in the current session.
		You can then run Docker commands like docker ps or docker run
		
#swapoff -a 
	swapoff → Disables swap space on the system.
	-a 		→ Applies the action to all swap devices and files listed in /proc/swaps.
	In practice:
		It immediately turns off all active swap areas (both swap partitions and swap files).
		After running it, the system will rely only on physical RAM. [ virtual memory to be off ]
		If RAM usage exceeds available memory, processes may fail or be killed by the OOM (Out Of Memory) killer.
	Why it’s used:
		Often required before resizing partitions or disabling swap permanently.
		Common in Kubernetes setups, because kubelet expects swap to be disabled for performance and scheduling consistency.
		Used in troubleshooting memory performance issues.

