#vi /etc/docker/daemon.json
{
 "exec-opts": ["native.cgroupdriver=systemd"]
}
==============================================
	That snippet is configuring Docker’s daemon.json file to set the cgroup driver:
	What it means:
		exec-opts 					→ Options passed to the Docker daemon when it starts.
		native.cgroupdriver=systemd → Tells Docker to use systemd as the cgroup driver instead of the default cgroupfs.
	Why it’s important:
		Kubernetes (and many modern container orchestration tools) expect Docker to use the same cgroup driver as the host system.
		On most Linux distros, systemd is the init system and manages cgroups.
		If Docker uses cgroupfs while Kubernetes uses systemd, you can get resource conflicts or errors like:

