#sudo yum install -y yum-utils device-mapper-persistent-data lvm2
	yum-utils
		Provides extra utilities for YUM (like yum-config-manager, repoquery, etc.).
		Useful for managing repositories and troubleshooting package issues.

	device-mapper-persistent-data
		Required for Docker’s overlay2 and devicemapper storage drivers.
		Provides persistent metadata storage for device-mapper thin provisioning.
	lvm2
		Logical Volume Manager tools.
		Needed when Docker uses the devicemapper storage driver, since it relies on LVM for managing thin pools.

#sudo mkdir -p /etc/containerd
#containerd config default | sudo tee /etc/containerd/config.toml
	What it does:
		containerd config default 				→ Generates the default configuration file for containerd in TOML format.
		| sudo tee /etc/containerd/config.toml 	→ Pipes the output into tee, which writes it to /etc/containerd/config.toml with elevated privileges (sudo).
		The result: You now have a full default config file saved at /etc/containerd/config.toml.
	Why it’s used:
		By default, containerd may run without a config file, using built-in defaults.
		Creating /etc/containerd/config.toml gives you a baseline file you can edit for custom settings (like SystemdCgroup = true, registry mirrors, snapshotter options, etc.).
		This is a common step when preparing containerd for Kubernetes clusters, because kubelet often requires specific runtime settings.

